Part 1: Conceptual Questions

1.

a.

perf = b0 + b1adhd + b2condition + b3speed + b4adhd*condition

b.

perf = b0 + b1*adhd

c.

perf = b0 + b1adhd + b2condition + b3adhdcondition

2.

One complication of the testing of interactions with measured predictors is unreliability in the predictors. Unreliability significantly reduces power since reliability is a product term. Another complication is the restriction in range of the predictors; if a predictor does not vary much, it makes it harder to find a relationship between variables.

3.

The additive assumption is when you regress your outcome variable on two predictors and the slope of the outcome variable on one predictor does not change as a function on the other predictor. Because of this, you can add the effects of both predictors when you take the derivative. This assumption’s reasonableness depends on the specific context being studied. It emphasizes the importance of tailoring statistical approaches to the unique features of the research domain to ensure that the analysis is meaningful and valid within that context.

##

b0 is 3.76; this is the effect of time on confidence for participants who have a score of 0 on time and workshop. b1 is -0.24; this is the linear effect of time on confidence when statistically controlling for the quadratic effect of time and the linear effect of workshop. b2 is 0.017; this is the quadratic effect of time on confidence when statistically controlling for the linear effects of time and workshop. Practically, this is the curvature of the line and half the amount the slope changes at every observation. b3 is 0.055; this is the linear effect of workshop on confidence when statistically controlling for both the linear and quadratic effects of time. F(3,146)=9.24, p<.001, ηp2 time = .03, ηp2 time^2 = .07, ηp2 workshop = .0003.

scatterplot

7

We regressed confidence scores the quadratic effect of the time spent in medical school, the linear effect of time spent in medical school, and the linear effect of confidence workshop condition (coded -.5 for did not attend confidence- boosting workshop, and .5 for did attend confidence-boosting workshop). Time was mean-centered in the primary analyses. The overall effect of Time and workshop was significant, F(3,146) = 9.24, p < .001, with Time accounting for 20% of the total variance in Confidence.

The linear effect of Time was significant, b = 0.12, np2 = .13, p < .001, indicating longer time spent in medical school is associated with a higher confidence score. The quadratic effect of Time was also significant, b = .017, p = .001, np2 = .03, indicating that the magnitude of the Population effect increased by .034 for every additional quarter spent in medical school. As can be seen in the graph above, confidence scores increase the more quarters spent in medical school. However, the linear effect of Workshop was not significant, b = .055, p = .85, np2 = .0002, indicating that attending a confidence-boosting workshop was not associated with a change in confidence scores.

Overall, time spent in medical school had a quadratic effect on confidence scores, meaning the effect changes at each level of time. Additionally, adding confidence-boosting workshop attendance as a covariate had little effect on the outcome variable.

2.53 is the predicted GPA for hypothetical participants who were halfway between interventions and stem classes. 0.16 is the effect of STEM classes on GPA when controlling for intervention and their interaction. 0.105 is the effect of intervention when controlling for STEM classes and their interaction. 0.248 is the interaction effect of STEM classes and intervention when controlling for their individual effects.

4.

gpa = 2.53 + 0.16stem + 0.105intervention + .248stem*intervention gpa = 2.53 + 0.16(-.5) + 0.105intervention + .248(-.5)intervention gpa = 2.53 - 0.08 + .105intervention - 0.124intervention gpa = 2.45 - 0.019intervention

-0.019 is the simple effect of intervention for participants in a non-STEM course.

5.

a.

gpa = 2.53 + 0.16(-.5) + 0.105(.5) + .248(-.5)*(.5) gpa = 2.44

b.

gpa = 2.53 + 0.16(.5) + 0.105(.5) + .248(.5)*(.5) gpa = 2.72

c.

gpa = 2.53 + 0.16(-.5) + 0.105(-.5) + .248(-.5)*(-.5) gpa = 2.46

d.

gpa = 2.53 + 0.16(.5) + 0.105(-.5) + .248(.5)*(-.5) gpa = 2.50

Our model predicts a GPA of 2.53 for participants who were hypothetically halfway between STEM class conditions and for participants who were average in experience. Taking a STEM course is predicted to increase GPA by 0.15 when controlling for experience. Having more experience (one unit higher on content experience score) is predicted to increase GPA by 0.053 when controlling for STEM courses. 0.113 is how much the effect of experience on GPA differs between STEM and non-STEM classes. F(3,496) = 7.993, p < .001, np2 = .02.
